{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Somalia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Somalia]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 16 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=16|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 1\n| deaths = 2\n| confirmed_cases = 60<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yUeyjEmQW8I |title=Madaxweynaha Soomaaliya oo sheegay in 25 qof ay gaartay tirada Dadka qaba Karona Fayrus. |language=en |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Somalia]] in March 2020. There is great concern about the possibility of an outbreak in Somalia, due to the country's lawlessness, lack of control by the central government as well as the lack of healthcare infrastructure.<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\"/><ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\nSomalia is in a state of protracted military conflict; the central government lacks control over large parts of the country, and is at odds with several of the regional governments.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/><ref>[https://theglobalobservatory.org/2019/11/state-level-military-forces-potentially-turn-tide-war-al-shabaab/]</ref> Most of the rural areas are dominated by the terrorist group [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]], which has a history of disrupting humanitarian work.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/> It faces widespread poverty and hunger, leaving people vulnerable to an outbreak.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\nSomalia's healthcare infrastructure is weak;<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\"/><ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/> it ranks 194th out of 195 in the [[Global Health Security Index]].<ref name=\"AP nightmare\">{{cite news |title=In Somalia, coronavirus goes from fairy tale to nightmare |url=https://apnews.com/b23baf8f62dfda03b6ef73777175e8d9 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=AP NEWS |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The country has less than 20 [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] beds available.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March===\nOn 16 March, the first case in Somalia was confirmed.<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref> Somalia's Health Ministry reported that a Somali citizen was returning home from [[China]].<ref name=\"AA\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases/1767971|title=Somalia, Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|date=16 March 2020|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n\nOn 7 April, the government reported the eighth confirmed case, a 58-year-old Somali man with no travel history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus - Somalia: 8th case of Coronavirus confirmed in Somalia |url=https://www.cnbcafrica.com/africa-press-office/2020/04/07/coronavirus-somalia-8th-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-somalia/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=CNBC Africa |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the government confirmed the first death.<ref>{{cite news |title=Somalia has registered first death from coronavirus: health minister |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-somalia/somalia-has-registered-first-death-from-coronavirus-health-minister-idUSKCN21Q2L6?il=0 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, Somalia confirmed its second death from coronavirus on Sunday, Khalif Mumin Tohow, justice minister of [[Hirshabelle State|Hirshabelle state]], succumbed in Mogadishu's Martini hospital a day after he tested positive in [[Jowhar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somali-state-minister-dies-of-coronavirus-in-mogadishu/1801894|title=Somali state minister dies of coronavirus in Mogadishu|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April ,35 new cases confirmed , 32 from Mogadishu , 2 from Hargeisa and 1 from Borama .                                                                              \n\n==Responses==\nOn 15 March, the government banned passengers who had been to China, Iran, Italy, or South Korea in the past 14 days from entering Somalia. At that time the government had quarantined four people.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Somalia bans entry from worst-hit countries |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-somalia-bans-entry-from-worst-hit-countries/1766837 |website=aa.com.tr |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the government announced that schools and universities would be closed for 15 days effective from 19 March and that large gatherings were prohibited.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\nThe Somali Aviation Ministry ordered a suspension of all international flights for 15 days starting from Wednesday, 18 March,<ref name=\"AA\" /> with the possibility of exceptions for humanitarian flights.<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\">{{cite news |title=Somalia Confirms First Case of Coronavirus {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/somalia-confirms-first-case-coronavirus |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=VOA News |language=en}}</ref> The suspension affected [[khat]] imports from [[Kenya]], leading to economic difficulties for khat sellers in Somalia and growers in Kenya.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Hits Somalia's Khat Sellers {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-hits-somalias-khat-sellers |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref> Also on 18 March, Prime Minister [[Hassan Ali Khaire]] announced $5 million had been allocated to address the pandemic.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\nMohamed Mohamud Ali, chairman of Somali Medical Association, warned that the virus could kill many more people in Somalia than [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|in China]] or [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], because there are no testing kits in the country, and patients have to wait at least three days to get results from [[South Africa]].<ref name=\"risk greater than China\">{{cite news |last1=Mohamed |first1=Hamza |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Experts say Somalia risk greater than China |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-experts-somalia-risk-greater-china-200319052938789.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] leaders met to discuss COVID-19. Ahmed Khalif of [[Action Against Hunger]] warned that the extremist group has a history of blocking access for humanitarian workers, but may allow people to go elsewhere for treatment.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\nTwenty volunteer doctors from [[Somali National University]] went to Italy to help fight [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|the outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Somalia sending 20 doctors to help Italy fight virus |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-sending-20-doctors-to-help-italy-fight-virus/1782154 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Somaliland===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somaliland}}\n\n==Testing==\n\nSomalia lacks testing capacity, so test samples must be sent abroad for processing, which delays results.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n{{Portal bar|border=n|Somalia|Viruses|Current events|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic|Somaliland}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Somalia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Somalia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Somalia]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Somalia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Somalia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Somalia]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 16 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=16|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 1\n| deaths = 2\n| confirmed_cases = 60<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yUeyjEmQW8I |title=Madaxweynaha Soomaaliya oo sheegay in 25 qof ay gaartay tirada Dadka qaba Karona Fayrus. |language=en |access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Somalia]] in March 2020. There is great concern about the possibility of an outbreak in Somalia, due to the country's lawlessness, lack of control by the central government as well as the lack of healthcare infrastructure.<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\"/><ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\nSomalia is in a state of protracted military conflict; the central government lacks control over large parts of the country, and is at odds with several of the regional governments.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/><ref>[https://theglobalobservatory.org/2019/11/state-level-military-forces-potentially-turn-tide-war-al-shabaab/]</ref> Most of the rural areas are dominated by the terrorist group [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]], which has a history of disrupting humanitarian work.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/> It faces widespread poverty and hunger, leaving people vulnerable to an outbreak.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\nSomalia's healthcare infrastructure is weak;<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\"/><ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/> it ranks 194th out of 195 in the [[Global Health Security Index]].<ref name=\"AP nightmare\">{{cite news |title=In Somalia, coronavirus goes from fairy tale to nightmare |url=https://apnews.com/b23baf8f62dfda03b6ef73777175e8d9 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=AP NEWS |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The country has less than 20 [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] beds available.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March===\nOn 16 March, the first case in Somalia was confirmed.<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) - Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref> Somalia's Health Ministry reported that a Somali citizen was returning home from [[China]].<ref name=\"AA\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases/1767971|title=Somalia, Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|date=16 March 2020|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n\nOn 7 April, the government reported the eighth confirmed case, a 58-year-old Somali man with no travel history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus - Somalia: 8th case of Coronavirus confirmed in Somalia |url=https://www.cnbcafrica.com/africa-press-office/2020/04/07/coronavirus-somalia-8th-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-somalia/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=CNBC Africa |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the government confirmed the first death.<ref>{{cite news |title=Somalia has registered first death from coronavirus: health minister |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-somalia/somalia-has-registered-first-death-from-coronavirus-health-minister-idUSKCN21Q2L6?il=0 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, Somalia confirmed its second death from coronavirus on Sunday, Khalif Mumin Tohow, justice minister of [[Hirshabelle State|Hirshabelle state]], succumbed in Mogadishu's Martini hospital a day after he tested positive in [[Jowhar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somali-state-minister-dies-of-coronavirus-in-mogadishu/1801894|title=Somali state minister dies of coronavirus in Mogadishu|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April ,35 new cases confirmed , 32 from Mogadishu, 2 from Hargiesa and 1 from Borama .                                                                              \n\n==Responses==\nOn 15 March, the government banned passengers who had been to China, Iran, Italy, or South Korea in the past 14 days from entering Somalia. At that time the government had quarantined four people.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Somalia bans entry from worst-hit countries |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-somalia-bans-entry-from-worst-hit-countries/1766837 |website=aa.com.tr |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the government announced that schools and universities would be closed for 15 days effective from 19 March and that large gatherings were prohibited.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\nThe Somali Aviation Ministry ordered a suspension of all international flights for 15 days starting from Wednesday, 18 March,<ref name=\"AA\" /> with the possibility of exceptions for humanitarian flights.<ref name=\"Somalia Confirms First Case VOA\">{{cite news |title=Somalia Confirms First Case of Coronavirus {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/somalia-confirms-first-case-coronavirus |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=VOA News |language=en}}</ref> The suspension affected [[khat]] imports from [[Kenya]], leading to economic difficulties for khat sellers in Somalia and growers in Kenya.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Hits Somalia's Khat Sellers {{!}} Voice of America - English |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-hits-somalias-khat-sellers |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=www.voanews.com |language=en}}</ref> Also on 18 March, Prime Minister [[Hassan Ali Khaire]] announced $5 million had been allocated to address the pandemic.<ref name=\"risk greater than China\"/>\n\nMohamed Mohamud Ali, chairman of Somali Medical Association, warned that the virus could kill many more people in Somalia than [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|in China]] or [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], because there are no testing kits in the country, and patients have to wait at least three days to get results from [[South Africa]].<ref name=\"risk greater than China\">{{cite news |last1=Mohamed |first1=Hamza |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Experts say Somalia risk greater than China |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-experts-somalia-risk-greater-china-200319052938789.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] leaders met to discuss COVID-19. Ahmed Khalif of [[Action Against Hunger]] warned that the extremist group has a history of blocking access for humanitarian workers, but may allow people to go elsewhere for treatment.<ref name=\"AP nightmare\"/>\n\nTwenty volunteer doctors from [[Somali National University]] went to Italy to help fight [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|the outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Somalia sending 20 doctors to help Italy fight virus |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-sending-20-doctors-to-help-italy-fight-virus/1782154 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Somaliland===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somaliland}}\n\n==